{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_crane_ver01/data/sn86089568/00517176564/1937090801/0739.xml":{"full_text":"16 PIECE ORCHESTRA FOR JAYSEE MUSICAL\nHOME\nEDITION\n56TH YEAR\n300 Chiriese Refugees Killed, 400 More Are Injured\nSURVEY SITES FOR TWO BIG_RIO\nGRANDE DAMS IN LAREDO SECTION\nNS\nBy RAY TUCKER\nD!SI'UR.BZD: The brakes which\nseveral prophets persuaded\nPresident Roosevelt to apply to the\n\u201cboom\u201d last spring threaten grave\nconsequences to the New Deal fin\naneial setup. It has also provoked a\nbackstage row between Secretary\nMorgenthau and the Federal Reserve\nChairman.\nIt was Mr. Eccles who sold F. D.\nR. the notion that the nation faced\nserious danger of uncontrolled indus\ntrial expansion and price inflation\u2014\nduring Mr. Morgenthau\u2019s absence\nfrom Washington, incidentally. Mr.\nRoosevelt sounded a public warn\ning, curtailed heavy P. W. A, spend\ning, increased reserve requirements,\nraised rediscount rates. Hardly a\nsingle prediction has been fulfilled,\nand the outcome may dry up the\ngovernment's souree of new funds.\nNow that crops are moving and\nprivate industry expanding, the banks\nhive been flooded with demands for\nshort-time loans. But because of\nthe increased resfrves requirements,\nthey have been selling government\nbonds instead of borrowing from the\nreserve or other institutions on their\ncommercial paper, That has depres\nsed the price of federal securities and\nhampered the Treasury\u2019s early fali\nfinancing. So the frown on the\nMorgenthau countenance was deeper\nthan the Grand Cenyon when he\nlanded at the Capital after a fast\nflight from San Francisco.\ns\nBRIGHT: The business outlook for\nthe final qu\u00e9rter of 1937 is fun\ndamentally favormble, despite sev\neral unsettling factors. The economic\nsharks at the Capital look for a\nsteady upward trend due to general\nfall activity, larger automobile qa!es'\nafter model change-overs, crop move\nments, increasing production.\nThe chief cloud consists of a fall\nin farm income, though \u00a71 wheat and\n10 cent cotton (maybe more) will\nmaintain egricultural purchasing\npower at a fair level, Larger crops,\nthough marketed at lower prices,\nwill mean greater diffusion of spend\ning money, too. Industrial payroils\nare far higher then a year ago, show\ning much greater gain than reem\nployment, end_retail trade has not\nsuffered as d\u2018rp a seasongl slump\nas usual, Higher prices in foods, fin\nished goods clothing and furniture\u2019\nand in articles affected by the price\nresale law have produced a hint of\nconsumer resistance.\nEconomically, we are sitting on one\nof our loftiest peacetime peaks and\nwe have been relaxing there since\nApril, when production hit the index\nfigure of 115 after a twosyear climb\nfrom 85 in the spring of 1935. \u2018the;\nmaintenance of that figure for almost\nsix months, despite foreign wars and\ndomestic turmoil (strikes and radical\nlegislative proposals, has made\n\u201ccheerio\u2019 'again a word of common\nusage on Main Street and Wall Street.\nPROGWS: Political wise hoys\n(and certain shrewd labor lead\ners) regard recent tart exchanges be\ntween New Deal spokesmen and C\n1. O.-er John L. Lewis as only an\nexcellent exhibition of shadow box\ning designed to allay fears based on\nthe close friendship between the\nWhite House and the United Mine\nchieftain.\nPrivately the President and the C.\n1. O. generalissimo appear to respect\nbut suspect each other\u2019s aims, as 1s\nnatural for two strong minded indi- l\nviduals. But each knows how far\nContinued on Page D I\nNo. 75\nBOMBED IN BOX\nCARS BY THE\nJAPS\nBoth Sides Warn\nForeign Ships To\nKeep Out Of\nWar Path\nSHANGHAI, Sept. 8\u2014(#)\u2014Three\nhundred Chinese non-combatants\nwere killed and 400 injured today\nwhen Japanese airplanes bombed\nrailroad cars packed with refugees.\nJapanese captured strategic Paoshan,\n12 miles north Shanghai, after dar\ning engineers blasted the 40-foot\nwalls.\nBoth sides deminded conditions\nmaking American-French-British neu\ntrality proposals ineffective.\nChinese warned foreign shipping\nout of the way of plapned reprisals\nagainst the Japanese coastsl block\nade. 4\nThe Tokyo diet enacted a 800 mil\nlion dollar war budget.\nPERISCOPE\ns Wi s TR 1\nHere's Dr. Powell and already get\nting data on the First Civic Music\n-m 4\nAnd Rex Shanks s going to Brain\nstorm some interesting facts about\n\"hm probably tomorrow or next\n\u2018hy.\n\u2018l\u2019myMullnhdmwn-hm\ntiful Van Dyke on his vacation but\nhis nerve failed him and he shaved\nno!!bdonmdnl\u2018bukhm.\nHello here Mr. and Mrs. Philip\nKazen. b\nThere\u2019s Reyes Ortiz in his beautiful\nyard.\nAnd here we have Jennie Good\nman and Mrs. Ed Cole talking first\nabout this and then about that and\nversa vice.\nShirley D?n always well\ndressed and wears a coat mosi\nof the time during the summer.\nPaul Young and Chester Wine de\nciding the price Is too great to pay\nat their ages to try to become grest\nmusicians.\ne oo\n\u2018Schoolgirl Admits\nFatally Shooting\nMale Attacker\nISELIN, New Jersey, Sept. 8\u2014(#)\u2014\nMargaret Drennan, 20, schoolgirl,\nadmitted today, Police Chief George\nKeating announced, she fatally shot\nPsul Reeves, 21, and father of two\nchildren,when he attempted to at\ntack her. She was the \u201clady in red\u201d\nseen running from the bungalow\nwhere Reeves was hot last night\nwhile his wife was at a theatre.\nPanhandle Rains\nAMARILLO, Sept. 8\u2014(#)\u2014Flooded\nstreams, fed by torrential rains, dis\nrupted train service north of Pan\nhandle, and eastern New Mexico to\nday.\n40 and 8 To Hold\nMonthly Meeting\nN s\nThe Laredo Volture of the\nand 8 holds fts regular monthly\nmeeting Thursday evening at 8\no'clock at Legion Home.\nDon\u2019t say the new commander,\nM. M. Valentine, hasn\u2019t warned\nyou. \u201cTell them foday that the\nvoltur\u00e9 meets tomorrow night,\nthen they ecan cancel all their\nother Thursday night dates\u201d Val\nentine said.\n\u201cThursday we'll tell them what\nwe are going to do\u201d, Val added.\nThe Laredn Times\n\"8 PAGES\nStudy Sites For Two Dams Near Laredo\nHere are officials of two governments who last week-end visited the sites of two dams proposed on the\nRio Grande mear Laredo. One would be between Laredo and Eagle Pass at Sullivan Springs the other\nbetween Laredo and\u2018Roma at Salinefio.\nLeft to rllh(/: John Savage, desi gner of Boulder Dam; L. M. Lawson, American commissioner of the\nIBC; J. Pedrero Cordova, Mexican commissioner of the IBC; A. M. Amor, chief hydraulic engineer of\nthe Mexican Water Commission; F rank Mcintire, assistant counsel for the American section of IBC; and\nC. M. Ainsworth, consulting engin eex for the American section.\nBritish Cabinet Holds Crisis Meet\nLONDON, Sept. 0\u2014(#)\u2014Three Brit\nish destroyers and three French war\nships sped today to the scene of a\nracing Mediterranean naval Lbttle\nbetween Spanish insurgents and gev\nernment ships.\nThe British cabinet held a \u201ccrisis\u201d\nmeeting over the alarming rift be\ntween Italy and Russia. British des\ntroyers were ordered to patrol bat\ntle area \u2018so as to be near possible\ntrouble.\u201d\nThe Soviet sent a second bitter\nmessage to Rome, declaring Italy's\n_denial of a Soviet charge an Italian\n\u2018submarine sank. RusSian shipy was\n\u201c\u2018entirely unacceptable.\u201d\nCITY T0 BUY\nNEW STREET\nMACHINERY\nThe old street sweeper which has\nserved Laredo during the past 14\nyears and kept the paved thorough\nfares of the city clean is to be re\ntired as soon as a new and modern\nsweeper can be purchased.\nAt the meeting of the city council\nTuesday night a resolution was pass\ned authorizing Mayor Martin to call\nfor bids for furnishing a motor-driven\nstreet sweeper, a motor-driven grader\nfour trucks and two motor-driven\nstreet sprinklers.\nFunds for the purchases of these\nitems of street machinery are pro\nvided in the $50,000 recently voted in\nthe 200,000 bond issue, of which $50,-\n000 was for street machinery and im\nprovements. Plars are also being pre\n\u2018pared at this time for streef improve\nments.\nJames Kilday Put\nOn A. 1. Board\n5 By Allred\nAUSTIN, Sept. 8 Governor\nAllred today appointed James Kil\nday, Houston, to succeed Claude Pol\nlard, Austin, as member of the board\nof regents of the College of Arts and\nIndustries, Kingsvillee Mrs. Loraine\n\u20188poonh. Corpus Christi, and R. C.\nEckhardt, XKingsville were reap-\nDr. William Dickens, Greenville,\nwas named a board of health mem\nber, succeeding Dr. S. A. Woodard,\nFort Worth, deceased. 4\nLAREDO, TEXAS, WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 8, 1937\n]i\u2019muun KC\nMEET TONIGHT\nThe regular Wednesday night meet\ning of the Knights of Columbus will\ntake place tonight at the Knights of\nColumbus Hall with a special pro\ngram. i\nRicardo Reyna, chairman in charge\nof the program, gaid that activities\nwould get underway at 8:30 and that\nsomething out of the ordinary would\nbe offererd on the program, refresh\nments also being included. All mem\nbers are urged to be present.\nSucker Advertising\nLaredo was not excepted when Barnum observed\n\u201cThere is a sucker born every minute.\u201d\nLaredo merchants are allowing themselves to be\ngypped of thousands of dollars annually by fly-by-night,\ncatch-as-catch-can disreputable advertising fakirs.\nThese unsavory salesmen hit the city and their sole\nobject is to mulet Laredo merchants through devious ad\nvertising schemes. Right now there are such schemes be\ning foisted on Laredo advertisers,\nLaredo merchants, through not doing as most other\ncities have done and organizing a central agency to pass\non advertising projects, have lost thousands upon thousands\nof good advertising dollars. These lost dollars do local\nmerchants no good and serve only to line the pockets of\ndisreputable and floating advertising quacks who can not\nhold a steady job and must thus take this means of simpli\nfied hi-jacking to make a living.\nA cehtral committee of merchants to pass on the merits\nof these propositions is long overdue. Those which will\ngive the merchant bona fide circulation and value received\nshould be accepted and the others should be rejected. When\n'a merchant spends advertising dollars he expects results.\nTo get results he must get circulation and distribution,\nFor a mealy-mouthed, and unknown, salesman to say\nthere is going to be some thousand circulation on such and\nsuch a project, doesnt\u2019 make that a fact. Such a salesman\ncares not a whit if there is one tenth of that circulation so\nlong as he gets his commission and enough money to get to\nanother city which like Laredo allows such shysters to\noperate.\nLaredo merchants should quit spending advertis\ning dollars on sucker schemes.\nThe Laredo Post of the American Legion made a good\nstart on this proposition by proposing just such a bureau.\nPlans were presented the city attorney.\nThe Legion should be encouraged to get a report on\n\u2018this matter.\nWallace Says Food\nPrices Are Dropping\nWASTINGTON, Sept. 8\u2014(#)\u2014Sec\nretary Wallace said today food costs\nwere already beginning to decline\nbecause of larger crops the farmers\nare harvesting this year. He said the\ntrend should continue \u2018\u2018if we have a\nseries of normsl crop yields.\u201d He said.\nwholesale prices turned downward in\nAugust and large crops of corn and\nother livestock feeds indicated meat\nprices will follow next year,\nStocks Steady\nS P TIPS SR S TR\nNEW YORK, Sept. 8\u2014(#)\u2014Stocks\nwere stezdy today, gaining fractions\nof a point more as the war scare\nlost its force.\nR AT\nT0 BE PART OF\nFRIDAY NIGHT\nSHOW\nLightner Lines Up\u2018\nOutstanding Group\nof Laredoans For\nAccompaniment\nBy LOUIS JUDKINS\nLights! Curtain] Music!\nAnd What Music!\nDirector Jimmie Lightner promised\nto get an orchestra to play for the\nJunior Chamber of Commerce\u2019's mu\nsical comedy, \u201cSouth of Sonora,\u201d\nthat goes on the stage Friday night,\nbut we didn't expect him to get the\nPhiladelphia Symphony Orchestra.\nBut there\u2019s a 16-piece orchesfra\nH for the show that ecan get\nmore music out of a few notes than\nanything you've ever heard.\nJimmie says, \u2018\u201cThere\u2019s only one\nthing wrong with the orchestra. [t's\nso darn good I don\u2019t have anything\nto fuss at them about and that\nleaves me in a dickens of a shape.\u201d\nFirst violins in the orchestra are\nJose Sompean, Jose Compean, Jr.,\nMiss Jean Sus Phillips, and Mrs. C.\nJ. Hinton Jr., And they don't just\nfiddle around, either. Second vio\nlins are Miss Margarita Farias and\nMiss Frances Crawford. Just be\ncause they play second violins is no\nsign they play second fiddle to any\none as these misses know how to\nhandle their bows.\nAndrew Phillips plays the cello,\n(Continued on Page 8)\nMORE STREET\nLIGHTS FOR\nCITY SOON\nWith the depression decisively a\nTexas Mostly cloudy tonight and\nto the old injunction, \u201clet there be\nlight.\u201d Street lights that were in\ncluded in the curtailment of city ex\npenses during the depression will\nsoon again provide illumination in\nthe residential sections of Laredo.\nFollowing the presentation of an\nappligation for a light in a certain\nresidential section to the city council\nTuesday night Mayor Albert Martin\ninformed the city council members\nthat at this time a survey is being\nmade to provide more street lights.\nHe said this survey would include\nthe numerous street lights that were\nshut off several years ago and would\nprovide for restoration of these lights\nwithin a very short time.\nManhunt Staged By\nTwo States For\nCop Killers\nGULFPORT, Mississippi, Sept. 8\u2014\n(#)\u2014Police of two states were search\ning today for three men, a\u2018rmed with\npistols \u00bbnd a machine gun, who fled\nafter fatally wounding patrolman, J.\n0. Wolff. Two Texans, alleged com\npenions, were jailed pending the out\ncome of the manhunt,\nDarwin Man Dies\nArtenio Moran, 45, a native of\nDarwin, in the coal mines region 23\n\u2018miles northwest of Laredo, died at\nhis home at Darwin Tuesday after\nnoon at 3:30 o'clock after a linger\ning illness. He had been engaged in\ncozl mining at the mines there for a\nnumber of years.\nHe is survived by his widow and\nother relatives. Funeral services\nwere held at Darwin this morning at\n8 o'clock, with interment in the\n\u2018cemetery at that place,\nThis By John Savage Who\nDesigned Boulder Dam And\nOther Great U. S. Projects\nHe Accompanied By Members Of The\nInternational Boundary Commission\nOf The United States and Mexico;\nSites, Sullivan Springs, Salineno\nPlans for the construction of two great irrigation and\nstorage dams in the Laredo territory on the Rio Grande,\none above and the other below this city, are taking tangible\nforms with surveys being made the past weekend by high\nUnited States and Mexico government officials,\nAmong those on the ground and looking over the dam\nsites are John Savage, the United States government\u2019s ace\nengineer and dam designer who drew the plans for Boulder\ndam. Accompanying Savage on this tour of inspection\nwere members of the International Boundary Commission.\nThe proposed dams which will extend Laredo\u2019s\nirrigated farm territory beyond Eagle Pass on the North\nand to Roma on the South will be located at Sullivan Springs\n?{etween here and Eagle Pass and at Salinefio just north of\noma.\nThese two dams have been given'\nserious consideration by the United\nStates and Mexican governments a\nnumber of years. Both governments\nhave made exhaustive surveys and\nrecommendations.\nThe fact that the ace dam designer\nof the United States government has\nnow finally visited the sites is taken\nas an indication that the government\nis ready to soon start actual work on\nthese projjects.\nThese two dams would mean the\nvirtual extension of the present\nfertile Rio Grande Lower Valley\nfrom Roma to Del Rio with Laredo\nthe hub. Not only as an irrigation\nprojection but the hydro-electric\npossibilities of the dam would also\nmean much to this great area.\nEngineer Savage and members of\nthe International Boundary Commis\nsion spent some time last week in\nspecting the dam site area to the\n(Continued on Page 8)\nANOTHER NEW\nPAVED AREA\nCONSIDERED\nWith the starting of construction\nwork on the paved roadway from a\nconection with Guadalupe street to\nMalinche avenue to the municipal\nairport and the Casa Blanca Country\nClub building through appropriation\nfor the work made by the county\ncommissioners court and awarded to\nH. B. Zachry for approximately\n$21,000, a movement is now on foot\nto have the city pave another im\nportant roadway leading to the air\nport and country club.\nThis latter pavement wo\u00e9uld be\nfrom Santa Maria eastward to a con\nnection with San Bernardo along\nSaunders street to a connection with\nSan Bernardo and from there east\nward along Saunders to a, connection\nwith the new paved roadway now\nunder construction to the airport and\ncountry club.\nThis new hard-surfaced roadway\nwould do much to relieve traffic\nover the roadway now to be paved\nas well as providing a short cut to\nthe airport and country club from\nhe northeastern section of the city\nand not necessitate traveling over the\ngravel roadway or going out Guada\nlupe to take the paved roadway to\nthe country club It would prove a\nboon to auto traffic.\nIt would also give another paved\nroute to the city\u2019 cemeteries. J\nAllred Expected\nSeek 15 Million\nMore In Taxes\nAUSTIN, Sept. 8\u2014(#\u2014Gov. Allred\nand members of the senate economy\ncommittee today studied the state's\nfinancial ills. Allred was expected\nto ask the legislature for lddiuonal\u2018\ntaxes of 15 miillion dollars year.\nA THOUGHT\nA DAY\nAND THE FAME OF DAVID\nWENT OUT INTO ALL LANDS;\nAND THE LORD BROUGHT THE\nFEAR OF HIM UPON ALL NA\nTIONS.\u2014Chronicles 14:17.\nHIKE COTTON\nESTIMATE\nWASHINGTON, Sept. $\u2014(#)\u2014The\nDepartment of Agriculture reported\ntoday a cotton crop of 16,930,000 bales\nof 50 pounds each is indicated this\nyear, basing the estimate on acreage\nand condition of the crop Septem\nber 1.\nThe census bureau announced\n1,871,403 running bales already ginned\nthis year,\nA month ago the department re\nported an indicated a erop of 15,543,000\nbales.\nThe production last year was\n12,398,882 bales.\nTexas cotton was estimated at\n4,622,000 bales.\nSheppard Blames\nSupreme Court\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 8\u2014(7)\u2014Sen\nator Sheppard of Texas said today\nincreased estimate cotton \u201c#howed\nthe havoc\u201d wrought by the supreme\ncourt\u2019s invalidation of the AAA.\nMarket Dips Again\nb G ST TE T e e e\nNEW ORLEANS, Sept. 8\u2014(#\u2014Cot\nton prices dropped a dollar a bale\ntoday after the department of agri\nculture indicated the fifth largest cot\nton crop on record.\nWATCH\nThursday\u2019s\nTimes For\nList Of\n-SPECIAL-\nWinners In\nThe Big\nPHOO\nCONTEST\nSponsored By\nPiggly Wigglw Stores\nMontrose Grocery\nCavazos Cash Grocery\nAlfredo Santos Grocery\nPRICE \u00a7e","height":"20280","width":"15364"}}
